I've tried it. Made my throat scratchy and when I wasn't chewing I still smoked
I have not tried it but I am open minded
Thanks for sharing your views!
#15: Gradually reducing the amount you smoke can also lead to quitting. Do you think gradual reduction could be right for you? #beingconscious
Yes
Yes. Down from 15-20 a day to 3-5 already!
That's is the method I'm trying
Glad to hear! (y)
#19: Would you consider using a nicotine inhaler to quit smoking? Why or why not? #beingconscious
No. I want to get away from nicotine, not get it from something else
I have never even heard of that I would have to do some research before considering it. 10491 makes a great point though nicotine is something I need to get away from
I am open minded but would need more info

#18: This over-the-counter Nicotine Replacement Therapy looks like cough drops and can help alleviate withdrawal symptoms during work or class. Would you try this method? Why or why not? #beingconscious
I would try but I am curious is it going to taste nasty
The taste would prevent me
I suppose I could try. I'd rather eat jelly beans though...

data.message: #13: Asking you to go out and party, even though they know drinking is a trigger, would NOT be helpful. Joking about how long you’ll stay on the quit wagon would NOT be helpful. What other things could you ask your friends NOT to do to keep you on the right path? #support
Smoking around me
Asking if I want a smoke
Just don't offer me any. Rest is on me.

#11: Now that you’ve shared about your top reasons for quitting, let’s consider your top reason NOT to quit. Post your #1 Con for quitting and tell us why it’s your biggest concern. You can finish this sentence: "I want to quit smoking, but I'm worried that ________." Feel free to discuss with other group members your concerns about quitting. #freeyourself
I don't have enough self.control
I really crave cigarettes
I want to quit but I'm worried that I'm not gonna be able to get through work without them
Thanks for sharing your concerns.
#8: Check out this site to see just how much $ you've given to Big Tobacco. Share your numbers here and vow to stop throwing away your hard-earned cash! #beingconscious
data.name: Cigarette Calculator
data.caption: www.cancer.org
data.description: Find out how many cigarettes are consumed over a given period of time. You supply the number of cigarettes or packs and the amount of time. Then press the "Calculate" button. "Reset" will let you try...

data.message: 525 packs dang. I really want to quit now.
Almost 1000 packs lol
Thanks for sharing your numbers.

#12: When you’re quitting, your friends and family may be eager to help out in any way that they can. Pick your favorite option below or suggest your own. Why would this option be helpful to you? #support• Go places where smoking is not allowed• Send you daily/weekly words of encouragement• Quit smoking with you
They can support me when I'm angry. I'd like them to quit with me for moral support.
I think being allowed to smoke in certain places would be helpful
#10: What are your top reasons for quitting? #freeyourself
Money, and my smokers cough
My son
Money and health

Since you told us at the beginning of the study that you are ready to quit smoking, I was wondering if anyone of you may be ready to set a quit date already? (Experts agree this is the most effective way to quit for good). #TDII
I have not put much thought in to a date yet

Hi 10456 - think about it. I can definitely recommend picking a date and running with it, but it's your decision really. Have you thought more about the things we talked about last week? For example nicotine replacement?
I have to run. Join me for our first smoking cessation advice session tomorrow if you'd like! See you.
August 15th

#9: Write a list of all the reasons why you want to quit, and post it somewhere prominent where you will frequently see it. Which spot did you choose, and why will it work for you? #reinforcement
Put a list on the back of my bedroom door. Set a date. Today.
On my refrigerator
I will put it on my home screen of my phone because I look at that every day

#7: Flavored cigarettes have been outlawed for years now, yet e-cig companies are using old tricks to gain new customers while they still can. Would you have started smoking at an earlier age if the product you used was flavored like your favorite candy? #ecig
I started smoking when I was really young. I guess  it could appeal to younger people
I probably would have enjoyed smoking more with flavored cigarettes.  Which might have made my addiction happen more quickly.
I started smoking for the head rush. Not sure if Flavored smoke would have impacted my habits.

#5: Big tobacco companies aim to make their brand appealing. Become more conscious and learn to critique cigarette ads. In the ads below, how is Camel trying to manipulate its customers? #beingconscious
They are trying to make it seem like beautiful people smoke
By making people think it's cool to smoke
Good points!
They make smoking look sexy
#4: Take this test to see how addicted to nicotine you are. What’s your reaction to your score? Are you surprised? #beingconscious
data.name: Assess Your Risk - Fagerstrom Test for Nicotine Dependence
data.caption: www.nova.edu
data.description: Several questions you completed on the smoking questionnaire can be added together to give us an idea of your level of dependence on nicotine. Higher scores typically reflect higher dependence on nicotine.

data.message: I scored in the highly dependent. I agree  with the score
Moderately dependent and I am not suprised.
Thanks for taking the test and sharing your results!
Highly dependent. Not surprised at all. I'm smoking one now...

#6: For any of you who aren’t sure what e-cigs are, take a look at this FDA page explaining what they are and some of the controversy surrounding their regulation. If you were a minor, do you think an e-cig would be more appealing or “safer” to try than a traditional cigarette? #beingconscious
data.name: Electronic Cigarettes (e-Cigarettes)
data.caption: www.fda.gov
data.description: Electronic cigarettes, also known as e-cigarettes, are battery-operated products designed to deliver nicotine, flavor and other chemicals. They turn chemicals, including highly addictive nicotine, into...

data.message: More appealing yes but I'm not sure about safer, further research has to be done.
Yes
Definitely more appealing. Trix flavored e-cigs? Come on now... Can't be good for you though
#3: Have any of you used a quit program or counseling program before? There are lots of free programs out there - how could they benefit you? What would make them better #beingconscious
No I have not
I have not
I haven't. It would benefit me if it seemed more real.
#2: What is keeping quitting smoking from the top of your priorities list? What would make quitting even more important to you? #motivation
I don't know what is keeping it from being a top priority. My son is my motivation for wanting to quit
The habit is keeping me from quitting. If I was to become sick that would motivate me to quit more.
General stress keeps me from quitting. It's easier to be a smoker than non-smoker. I want to quit for financial and health reasons.
Have you ever tried to quit or reduce your smoking? Which strategy did you choose and how did it go? #TDII
I tried cold turkey and trying to cut down. It didn't work out either time.
Thanks for sharing 10456 - so based on your past experiences what would you do differently in the future?
I have been thinking about trying the patch or something. It's really hard because I live in a house of smokers.
10456 - yes, that can make it very hard, but there may also be things other smokers could do. What could you ask them to do that would be helpful for you?
Also, I agree that nicotine replacement such as the patch can be very helpful - you can check out your options here: http://smokefree.gov/explore-medications
I can ask them to not smoke around me. I just don't want to impose on them but I think they would be supportive. I will  check our the link thanks.
You know if my experience smokers are usually quite happy to support someone else quitting if they can. Also you are just asking and that can't hurt, right? It may be worth to give it a try.
Yeah you are right.

Great 10456 - I've got to run, but I'll leave you with the 5 most important steps to stop smoking in my opinion: 1. I would recommend to pick a quit day and following through with it. 2. Get support from family/friends/colleagues. 3. Learn new skills and alternative behaviors for your high risk situations. 4. Depending on how much you smoke, I would definitely recommend that you consider trying some form of nicotine replacement therapy – we know that using these can dramatically decrease your cravings and withdrawal and increase your chances to quit for good. 5. Be prepared for relapse or difficult situations (e.g., alcohol, being around other smokers, stress, etc.). I know this sounds like a lot, but we will cover each of these aspects more in depth over the next weeks. How does this sound? Anything there you think may be useful?
See you next week! Bye.
I have tried cold turkey and slowly weening down neither were successful
Cold turkey, e-cigs, nicotine gum... Always end up buying another pack
#1: On a scale of 1-10, how important is it to you to quit smoking for good? #motivation

data.message: Welcome to the Tobacco Status Project! Thank you for joining us. We will start posting TOMORROW at 12 noon PDT! Here's how it works:1) We will share one post everyday for 90 days. Remember to turn on your notifications and check this page daily!2) Your group has been randomly assigned to a Weekly Incentive. To earn money, you must comment on ALL posts we share each week. You will earn $7 if you commented on all 7 posts, and $0 if you commented on 6 or less. We'll tally your comments every week, and you'll have a new chance to earn money at the start of the next week. You will receive a gift card for the money you've earned at the end of the 90-day program.3) Dr. Johannes Thrul will be joining us for 1 hour each week, during which he will answer any tobacco-related questions, share info and resources, and provide support to our group. Stay tuned for his first session TOMORROW!

Hello TSP members! We will be launching this group on WEDNESDAY! :D We want you to know that this secret group is a great place to share your thoughts and engage in conversation. Please feel free to like or respond to each others' comments and share any relevant content of your own.To begin, let's take a moment to get to know each other a little better. Feel free to share with us:• Where you come from• Anything about your smoking (how much, how often, when you first started, etc.)• What you hope to gain from participating in the Tobacco Study ProjectThank you! We hope you're as excited as we are!

Welcome to the Tobacco Study Project! We're so happy that you’re joining us and can't wait to start. We're still adding people to this secret group, but in the meantime feel free to look at our Consent Form and TSP Group Rules (below). Thanks for your patience and stay tuned!

data.message: This group is for 18-25 year olds who currently smoke and are ready to quit in the very near future. While your quit-date approaches, get educated about Nicotine Replacement Therapies, ways to prepare for and deal with cravings & triggers, grow your support system and learn the best techniques to quit and STAY quit.This group has been randomly selected to have Weekly Incentives; you can accumulate $7 at the end of every week in which you comment every day, for a gift card of up to $90 at the end of the session.
